# ── PRE-PUSH HOOK ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Runs BEFORE code is pushed to the remote repository.
# This is your last line of defence before code leaves your machine.
# If any check fails, the push is blocked.
#
# ── EXERCISE 12: SHOULD CYPRESS RUN IN PRE-PUSH? ────────────
#
# This hook now includes Cypress E2E tests after unit tests and
# frontend build. The goal is to evaluate whether this is a good
# idea in practice.
#
# PROS of running Cypress locally:
#   - Catches E2E failures before they reach CI
#   - Faster feedback than waiting for a remote pipeline
#   - Saves CI minutes (which cost money on paid plans)
#
# CONS of running Cypress locally:
#   - Requires the frontend dev server to be running
#   - Full suite takes 1-2+ minutes (slow for every push)
#   - Tests that hit the remote API (Render) depend on network
#   - Render cold starts can cause timeouts that aren't your fault
#   - Blocks the developer while tests run
#
# VERDICT:
#   Running the FULL Cypress suite in pre-push is usually too slow
#   and unreliable for everyday use. A better approach is:
#     - Pre-push: unit tests + build (fast, no network dependency)
#     - CI pipeline: full Cypress suite (runs in background, doesn't block you)
#     - Optional: run a SMALL subset of Cypress locally (e.g. debug-practice
#       tests that don't need API calls)
#
# For this exercise, we include the full suite to observe the timing
# and reliability issues firsthand.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 1. Run backend unit tests
# These are fast (< 1 second) and have no external dependencies.
# If your utility functions are broken, everything else will be too.
# Using a subshell (...) so the cd doesn't affect later commands.
echo "Running backend unit tests..."
(cd backend && npm test || exit 1)

# 2. Build the frontend
# Catches missing imports, JSX syntax errors, and env variable issues.
# Takes ~2-3 seconds locally. No network dependency.
echo ""
echo "Building frontend..."
(cd frontend && npm run build || exit 1)

# 3. Run Cypress E2E tests
# ⚠️  THIS IS THE PART TO EVALUATE.
#
# For Cypress to work, the frontend dev server MUST be running.
# If it's not running, Cypress will fail with:
#   "cy.visit() failed trying to load http://localhost:5173"
#
# This means the developer must:
#   a) Have the frontend running in another terminal, OR
#   b) The hook must start it (adds complexity and time)
#
# We start the dev server here, wait for it, run tests, then kill it.
# This adds ~15-30 seconds to every push.
echo ""
echo "Starting frontend dev server for Cypress..."
(cd frontend && npm run dev -- --host 0.0.0.0 > /dev/null 2>&1 &)

# Wait for the dev server to be ready.
# --timeout 30000 = 30 seconds. If it takes longer, something is wrong.
npx wait-on http://localhost:5173 --timeout 30000

echo "Running Cypress E2E tests..."
npx cypress run --browser electron
CYPRESS_EXIT=$?

# Clean up: kill the dev server we started.
# lsof finds the process on port 5173, kill stops it.
kill $(lsof -t -i:5173) 2>/dev/null

# If Cypress failed, block the push.
if [ $CYPRESS_EXIT -ne 0 ]; then
  echo ""
  echo "BLOCKED: Cypress E2E tests failed"
  exit 1
fi

echo ""
echo "All pre-push checks passed."
